Title:
Slack UDC2 BOF (Cobalt Strike UDC2 over Slack API)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This repository implements a Cobalt Strike Beacon Object File (BOF) that provides a UDC2 transport channel by encapsulating Beacon frames inside Slack API requests. It solves the problem of operating C2 traffic over a common SaaS platform to blend with legitimate outbound HTTPS traffic and traverse restrictive egress controls. The project includes a Windows in-memory BOF client (no MSVCRT, WinAPI-only) and a Python server component that relays extracted UDC2 frames to a Team Server UDC2 listener. It documents core UDC2 proxy functions (`udc2Proxy`, `udc2Close`) and uses WinINet for HTTP(S) communication to Slack. The implementation is intentionally simplified for learning and lacks fragmentation and multi-beacon routing, making it more suitable for lab/education than full-scale operations. Useful primarily for red teamers/pentesters learning UDC2/BOF transport development and for defenders studying Slack-based C2 tradecraft.

Technical Focus:
- Cobalt Strike UDC2 transport implementation
- Beacon Object File (BOF) development constraints (no CRT, in-memory)
- Slack Web API as a C2 carrier (message size limits, channel IDs, bot tokens)
- HTTP(S) communications via WinINet (`InternetOpenA`, `HttpSendRequestA`, etc.)
- Relay/proxy architecture (Python server forwarding to Team Server listener)
- Error handling and transport-layer limitations (timeouts, fragmentation)

Use Cases:
- Build a custom UDC2 transport that tunnels Beacon traffic through Slack
- Prototype/learn BOF-based network transports and UDC2 proxy mechanics
- Egress-restricted C2 experiments using SaaS endpoints over HTTPS
- Defensive testing: create detections for anomalous Slack bot/API usage patterns
- Lab simulation of “living-in-SaaS” C2 channels for threat emulation

Keywords:
Cobalt Strike, Beacon, UDC2, BOF, Beacon Object File, Slack API, Slack bot token, channel ID, WinINet, HTTP over TLS, proxy transport, C2 tunneling, Team Server, Python relay, Windows API, in-memory execution, fragmentation limit, SaaS C2, egress bypass, traffic encapsulation